olumns in your string_columns cleaning loop. Only clean scalar string columns.\n- NEVER pass DataFrames with list-valued cells directly to EmbeddingBlocker. Flatten list columns to strings first.\n- When writing a lower_strip or preprocess function, handle list inputs: `if isinstance(x, (list, tuple, set)): return " ".join(str(v).lower().strip() for v in x if pd.notna(v))`\n- Recommended list_strategy values per comparator type:\n  * StringComparator: "best_match", "set_jaccard", "set_overlap" (avoid "concatenate" — it merges all elements into one string, producing poor match quality on real lists)\n  * NumericComparator: "average" (default), "best_match", "range_overlap", "set_jaccard"\n  * DateComparator: "closest_dates" (default), "range_overlap", "average_dates", "latest_dates", "earliest_dates"\n- When values are delimited strings (e.g., "pop; rock; jazz"), use union(separator="; ") or intersection(separator="; ") as the fuser to properly split before merging.\n- For list-like fields where source quality varies, use `favour_sources(source_preferences=[...])` or `prefer_higher_trust(trust_map={...})` rather than blind union/intersection.\n- `intersection_k_sources(k=2)` is useful when 2+ source agreement signals correctness.\n- Ensure list normalization is consistent ACROSS sources before fusion (same delimiter, same casing, same element format).\n        \n\n        5. **BLOCKING CONFIGURATION** (pre-computed optimal blocking strategies):\n        This configuration was determined by a blocking evaluation agent. Use these settings\n        for your blocking step in the pipeline:\n        {\n  "blocking_strategies": {\n    "dbpedia_sales": {\n      "strategy": "semantic_similarity",\n      "columns": [\n        "name",\n        "platform",\n        "releaseYear"\n      ],\n      "params": {\n        "top_k": 20\n      },\n      "pair_completeness": 0.912621359223301,\n      "num_candidates": 929573,\n      "is_acceptable": true\n    },\n    "metacritic_dbpedia": {\n      "strategy": "semantic_similarity",\n      "columns": [\n        "name",\n        "developer",\n        "platform"\n      ],\n      "params": {\n        "top_k": 20\n      },\n      "pair_completeness": 0.9625668449197861,\n      "num_candidates": 409850,\n      "is_acceptable": true\n    },\n    "metacritic_sales": {\n      "strategy": "semantic_similarity",\n      "columns": [\n        "name",\n        "platform",\n        "releaseYear"\n      ],\n      "params": {\n        "top_k": 20\n      },\n      "pair_completeness": 1.0,\n      "num_candidates": 409504,\n      "is_acceptable": true\n    }\n  },\n  "id_columns": {\n    "dbpedia": "id",\n    "metacritic": "id",\n    "sales": "id"\n  }\n}\n\n        IMPORTANT: Use the id_columns and blocking_strategies from this config:\n        - Use the correct id_column for each dataset as specified\n        - Use the recommended strategy (exact_match_single/multi or semantic_similarity)\n        - Use the recommended columns for blocking\n        - Strategy to blocker mapping:\n          * exact_match_single / exact_match_multi -> StandardBlocker (exact match on columns)\n          * token_blocking / ngram_blocking -> TokenBlocker (token or n-gram blocking)\n          * sorted_neighbourhood -> SortedNeighbourhoodBlocker (window)\n          * semantic_similarity -> EmbeddingBlocker (top_k)\n        - Blocker API contract in this environment:\n          * materialize candidate pairs with `blocker.materialize()`\n          * do NOT call `.block()` on `EmbeddingBlocker`\n          * pass the materialized candidate DataFrame into `RuleBasedMatcher.match(..., candidates=...)`\n        - Correspondence artifact contract (mandatory):\n          * for each expected pair ["dbpedia_metacritic", "dbpedia_sales", "metacritic_sales"]\n          * save exactly one CSV file to `output/runs/20260322_175903_games/correspondences/correspondences_<left>_<right>.csv`\n          * each file must contain PyDI fusion-ready columns `id1` and `id2` (optional extra columns like `score` are allowed)\n          * do NOT invent alternate filename schemes\n          * do NOT rely on reloading or renaming correspondences later to make them usable\n          * fail fast if an expected pair\'s correspondence DataFrame is empty before fusion\n        \n\n        6. **MATCHING CONFIGURATION** (pre-computed comparator settings):\n        This configuration was determined by a matching evaluation agent. Use these settings\n        for your RuleBasedMatcher step in the pipeline:\n        {\n  "id_columns": {\n    "dbpedia": "id",\n    "metacritic": "id",\n    "sales": "id"\n  },\n  "matching_strategies": {\n    "dbpedia_sales": {\n      "comparators": [\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "name",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "platform",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "developer",\n          "similarity_function": "cosine",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "date",\n          "column": "releaseYear",\n          "max_days_difference": 365\n        }\n      ],\n      "weights": [\n        0.45,\n        0.2,\n        0.15,\n        0.2\n      ],\n      "threshold": 0.75,\n      "f1": 0.864367816091954\n    },\n    "metacritic_dbpedia": {\n      "comparators": [\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "name",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "platform",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "developer",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "date",\n          "column": "releaseYear",\n          "max_days_difference": 366\n        }\n      ],\n      "weights": [\n        0.45,\n        0.2,\n        0.2,\n        0.15\n      ],\n      "threshold": 0.8,\n      "f1": 0.8866995073891625\n    },\n    "metacritic_sales": {\n      "comparators": [\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "name",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "platform",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "string",\n          "column": "developer",\n          "similarity_function": "jaro_winkler",\n          "preprocess": "lower_strip",\n          "list_strategy": "concatenate"\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "numeric",\n          "column": "criticScore",\n          "max_difference": 5.0\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "numeric",\n          "column": "userScore",\n          "max_difference": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          "type": "date",\n          "column": "releaseYear",\n          "max_days_difference": 365\n        }\n      ],\n      "weights": [\n        0.35,\n        0.2,\n        0.15,\n        0.12,\n        0.08,\n        0.1\n      ],\n      "threshold": 0.78,\n      "f1": 0.8844884488448845\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n        IMPORTANT: Use the matching_strategies from this config:\n        - Build comparators (StringComparator/NumericComparator/DateComparator) for each dataset pair\n        - Use the specified weights and threshold.\n        - For each pair in `matching_strategies`, you **MUST** define a\n            variable named `threshold_[original_pair_key]` (e.g.,\n            `threshold_discogs_lastfm = 0.7`) with the corresponding threshold value.\n            Ensure your RuleBasedMatcher instances use these variables for their\n            `threshold` parameter.\n        - preprocess mapping: "lower" -> str.lower, "strip" -> str.strip, "lower_strip" -> lambda x: str(x).lower().strip()\n\n        - For NumericComparator on potentially list-valued columns (e.g., duration fields), set `list_strategy` explicitly (recommended: "average") or safely scalarize before matching.\n        - For DateComparator on multi-date columns, set `list_strategy` explicitly (recommended: "closest_dates").\n        \n\n        Your task is to **create a similar integration pipeline** so that it works with\n        the datasets provided. Output should only consist of the relevant Python code\n        for the integration pipeline.\n\n        OUTPUT PATHS (MANDATORY — use these exact paths, do NOT hardcode \'output/\'):\n        - Correspondences: save to `{correspondences_dir}/correspondences_<left>_<right>.csv`\n        - Fusion data: save to `{output_dir}/data_fusion/fusion_data.csv`\n        - Fusion debug: save to `{output_dir}/data_fusion/debug_fusion_data.jsonl`\n        - Create directories with `os.makedirs(..., exist_ok=True)` before writing.\n\n        FUSION RULES (MANDATORY):\n        - The output must always be the full fused dataset. Run `DataFusionEngine.run(..., include_singletons=True)`.\n        - Use PyDI built-in fusers as the default and strongly preferred choice.\n        - NEVER write custom fusion resolvers, lambda resolvers, or helper functions for fusion. Use ONLY PyDI built-in resolvers.\n        - The built-in resolvers cover ALL use cases: voting, longest_string, most_complete, median, average, earliest, most_recent, union, intersection, intersection_k_sources, prefer_higher_trust, favour_sources.\n        - For list-valued columns: use union(separator="; ") or intersection_k_sources(k=2, separator="; ").\n        - For trust-based selection: use prefer_higher_trust(trust_map={...}) or favour_sources(source_preferences=[...]).\n        - Do NOT manually post-process or overwrite `_fusion_confidence` outside the normal resolver return contract.\n        - ML MATCHER WARNING: When using MLBasedMatcher, clusters often contain MULTIPLE records per source dataset\n          (e.g. 5 discogs records + 3 lastfm records + 2 musicbrainz records in one cluster).\n          In this situation, `voting` is BIASED toward whichever source contributed more records to the cluster,\n          regardless of data quality. NEVER use `voting` as a primary resolver with ML matching.\n          Instead use `prefer_higher_trust` or `favour_sources` to select the most authoritative source,\n          or use `shortest_string`/`longest_string` which pick by value characteristics rather than majority.\n        - Choose fusion strategies based on EVIDENCE, not just data type:\n          * If one source is clearly more complete/accurate for an attribute (visible in input data samples or source agreement), use `prefer_higher_trust` with appropriate trust_map\n          * If sources have roughly equal quality, use `voting` for strings, `median` for numbers\n          * `longest_string` is excellent for text attributes where one source has more complete/detailed values (e.g., full label names vs abbreviations, complete genre lists vs partial). Consider it as a strong default for metadata text fields.\n          * `most_complete` is similar to longest_string but also considers non-null coverage. Good for attributes with many nulls in some sources.\n          * For numeric aggregates (e.g., total duration, page count): consider `maximum` when the target represents a "full" measurement — the maximum value often reflects the most complete source. Use `median` only when averaging across sources makes semantic sense.\n          * If mismatch samples show format differences (not value differences), fix normalization before fusion rather than switching fusers\n          * For list-like fields: use `intersection(separator=...)` or `intersection_k_sources(k=2)` when sources are noisy; use `union(separator=...)` only when both sources are clean and complementary\n          * For list-like fields where one source is clearly better, use `favour_sources(source_preferences=[...])` instead of union/intersection\n          * For dates: use `prefer_higher_trust` with data-driven trust ordering. Avoid `earliest` as a blanket default — it picks the oldest date regardless of correctness. Only use `most_recent` when diagnostics explicitly justify recency semantics\n          * IMPORTANT: Review the INPUT DATA SAMPLES section to see actual values from each source before choosing trust levels\n        - For trust-based fusion, pass trust configuration only at registration time:\n          `strategy.add_attribute_fuser(attr, prefer_higher_trust, trust_map=trust_map)`\n        - Do NOT wrap `prefer_higher_trust` in another function that hardcodes `trust_map` again.\n        - Avoid `most_recent` as a default temporal resolver unless diagnostics explicitly show recency is the correct target semantics.\n        - Avoid `union` for list-like fields when cluster purity is weak or list-format inconsistencies are present.\n\n        {PIPELINE_MATCHING_SAFETY_RULES_BLOCK}\n        \n            8. Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The main remaining errors are caused by fusion/post-clustering configuration, not blocking or matcher recall. Correspondence files are present and pairwise matching F1 is already high (~0.86-0.89), while cluster analysis shows severe one-to-many ambiguity and explicitly recommends MaximumBipartiteMatching. Current pipeline already added post-clustering, but attribute fusion is still misaligned with validation: releaseYear is plateaued at 0% despite source evidence showing metacritic is an exact 100% match to validation; publisher/developer/ESRB mismatches are largely source-choice and canonical-name selection issues. Some attributes are structurally limited: userScore remains noisy even in the best source (metacritic exact 29%), and criticScore has limited exact agreement. Protected attributes above 85% should remain unchanged.",\n  "next_node": "pipeline_adaption",\n  "reasoning": "This must go to pipeline_adaption because the fixes needed are resolver/trust/post-clustering choices, which are allowed there. Blocking/matching are not the bottleneck: correspondences are non-empty and F1 is strong. Normalization is not the first fix because the highest-impact failure, releaseYear at 0%, is not a source-format problem\\u2014the validation uses YYYY-MM-DD, and metacritic already matches that exactly 100%. The current fusion choice is simply selecting the wrong value. Likewise publisher and ESRB need source preference adjustments, and developer needs a resolver aligned to canonical-label behavior. Preserve the 11 attributes already above 85% by not changing them.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "A realistic ceiling with current sources is about 83-84% overall, consistent with the provided ceiling estimate. releaseYear, developer, publisher, and ESRB are materially improvable through fusion changes. userScore and criticScore appear partly structurally limited because no source consistently matches validation. So substantial improvement is available, but not perfect accuracy.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "releaseYear",\n      "issue": "Current resolver/priority is wrong. Accuracy is 0% even though source-vs-validation shows metacritic exact=100%, sales exact=93%, dbpedia exact=80%, all non-null.",\n      "fix": "Change releaseYear fuser to prefer_higher_trust with trust_map={\'metacritic\':5,\'sales\':4,\'dbpedia\':1}. Do not use earliest.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Validation clearly expects a canonical source value, not the chronologically earliest one. Among all sources, metacritic matches perfectly. prefer_higher_trust is the best resolver because one source is dominant. voting could still fail when all three disagree; earliest is already catastrophic; median/maximum/minimum are inapplicable for date strings. This is the highest-confidence fusion fix.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.087\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "developer",\n      "issue": "Current voting can select alternate or expanded names, while validation often expects a canonical short form (e.g., \'Traveller\'s Tales\' over \'TT Games\', \'London Studio\' over \'SCEE London Studio\'). Missing-fused cases should also reduce after post-clustering, but resolver choice still matters.",\n      "fix": "Change developer fuser from voting to prefer_higher_trust with trust_map={\'metacritic\':4,\'sales\':4,\'dbpedia\':1}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Source comparison shows metacritic exact=80%, sales exact=80%, dbpedia exact=73%, with higher fuzzy for dbpedia due to longer/variant forms. That pattern argues against longest_string and against plain voting when alias variants split votes. prefer_higher_trust over the two best sources avoids dbpedia\'s noisier canonicalization while still allowing either strong source to win. favour_sources was considered, but there is no clear single winner between metacritic and sales; equal top trust is safer.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.033\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "publisher",\n      "issue": "Publisher accuracy is dragged down by wrong source preference and canonical-name mismatches. Validation often prefers sales-style publisher labels, and sales is the only measured strong source (exact=80%).",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for publisher but strengthen attribute-level trust to {\'sales\':5,\'metacritic\':2,\'dbpedia\':1}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "This attribute has a clear best source. prefer_higher_trust is superior to voting because disagreement is common and only one source aligns well with validation. longest/shortest_string are poor fits because publisher variants are semantic aliases, not completeness differences. This should improve wrong-source picks while preserving already good behavior.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.029\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "ESRB",\n      "issue": "ESRB uses prefer_higher_trust, but the trust map should consistently favor metacritic, which aligns best with validation. Some remaining errors are representation variants like \'M\' vs \'M17+\', which normalization could later address if needed, but source choice is the first fusion fix.",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for ESRB and set trust_map={\'metacritic\':5,\'sales\':3,\'dbpedia\':1}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Metacritic is the strongest source for ESRB in the provided evidence. prefer_higher_trust fits better than voting because there are few sources and one is clearly superior. union/intersection are inappropriate for scalar ratings; longest/shortest_string are brittle for label variants. This is a low-risk source-selection improvement.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.029\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "post_clustering",\n      "issue": "Correspondence graphs remain highly ambiguous (one-to-many ~63-66%, ambiguity ratio >73%), so coherent entity grouping depends on post-clustering quality.",\n      "fix": "Preserve and standardize MaximumBipartiteMatching as the post-clustering step before fusion; ensure the fusion run uses only refined correspondences, not raw concatenated correspondences.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "The cluster analysis explicitly recommends MaximumBipartiteMatching as the top strategy. It is the best available intervention within pipeline_adaption for reducing malformed clusters and missing fused rows. StableMatching and HierarchicalClusterer were considered but are secondary recommendations. Since current code already applies MaximumBipartiteMatching, this is mainly a preserve/verify instruction to avoid regression.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.05\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "userScore",\n      "issue": "Low accuracy is mostly structural. Best source metacritic only achieves exact=29%, while sales is worse.",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for userScore with metacritic favored over sales, e.g. {\'metacritic\':5,\'sales\':2,\'dbpedia\':1}; do not spend the next iteration on alternative resolvers.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "A single best source exists, but it is weak. prefer_higher_trust is still the least-bad choice. voting will underperform when values differ numerically; median is not obviously better without evidence that validation reflects an aggregate; longest/shortest_string are nonsensical for numeric scores. This attribute is near its structural ceiling, so it should not drive the next iteration.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.01\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "criticScore",\n      "issue": "CriticScore has limited exact source agreement; sales is best aligned, metacritic mostly only fuzzy-matches.",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for criticScore with {\'sales\':5,\'metacritic\':2,\'dbpedia\':1}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Among available sources, sales is the clearest winner. prefer_higher_trust is the safest resolver for a numeric scalar when one source is known to be closer to validation. median was considered but lacks evidence and may create synthetic values not present in validation. This is mitigation rather than a major gain because the attribute is structurally limited.",\n      "cl