rce comparison shows metacritic exact=80%, sales exact=80%, dbpedia exact=73%, with higher fuzzy for dbpedia due to longer/variant forms. That pattern argues against longest_string and against plain voting when alias variants split votes. prefer_higher_trust over the two best sources avoids dbpedia\'s noisier canonicalization while still allowing either strong source to win. favour_sources was considered, but there is no clear single winner between metacritic and sales; equal top trust is safer.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.033\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "publisher",\n      "issue": "Publisher accuracy is dragged down by wrong source preference and canonical-name mismatches. Validation often prefers sales-style publisher labels, and sales is the only measured strong source (exact=80%).",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for publisher but strengthen attribute-level trust to {\'sales\':5,\'metacritic\':2,\'dbpedia\':1}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "This attribute has a clear best source. prefer_higher_trust is superior to voting because disagreement is common and only one source aligns well with validation. longest/shortest_string are poor fits because publisher variants are semantic aliases, not completeness differences. This should improve wrong-source picks while preserving already good behavior.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.029\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "ESRB",\n      "issue": "ESRB uses prefer_higher_trust, but the trust map should consistently favor metacritic, which aligns best with validation. Some remaining errors are representation variants like \'M\' vs \'M17+\', which normalization could later address if needed, but source choice is the first fusion fix.",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for ESRB and set trust_map={\'metacritic\':5,\'sales\':3,\'dbpedia\':1}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Metacritic is the strongest source for ESRB in the provided evidence. p