ed_match: names, titles, labels, artists, text fields (handles word reordering like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates where only the year matters\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings (use reasonable tolerance)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent or all-null), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and meaningful in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n- IMPORTANT: When the gold set has a parent column (e.g. "tracks") but the fused output has sub-columns\n  derived from it (e.g. "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"),\n  DROP the sub-columns from evaluation unless they have explicit corresponding columns in the gold set.\n  Evaluating derived sub-columns against a non-existent gold column produces zero accuracy and wastes\n  investigation cycles. Only evaluate attributes that have a direct 1:1 column match in the gold set.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(lambda x: float(x).is_integer()).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, use fused_id_column="eval_id" (NOT "_id" or "id").\n  The eval_id column is pre-computed to map cluster IDs back to validation-set source IDs.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The main remaining errors are caused by fusion/post-clustering configuration, not blocking or matcher recall. Correspondence files are present and pairwise matching F1 is already high (~0.86-0.89), while cluster analysis shows severe one-to-many ambiguity and explicitly recommends MaximumBipartiteMatching. Current pipeline already added post-clustering, but attribute fusion is still misaligned with validation: releaseYear is plateaued at 0% despite source evidence showing metacritic is an exact 100% match to validation; publisher/developer/ESRB mismatches are largely source-choice and canonical-name selection issues. Some attributes are structurally limited: userScore remains noisy even in the best source (metacritic exact 29%), and criticScore has limited exact agreement. Protected attributes above 85% should remain unchanged.",\n  "next_node": "pipeline_adaption",\n  "reasoning": "This must go to pipeline_adaption because the fixes needed are resolver/trust/post-clustering choices, which are allowed there. Blocking/matching are not the bottleneck: correspondences are non-empty and F1 is strong. Normalization is not the first fix because the highest-impact failure, releaseYear at 0%, is not a source-format problem\\u2014the validation uses YYYY-MM-DD, and metacritic already matches that exactly 100%. The current fusion choice is simply selecting the wrong value. Likewise publisher and ESRB need source preference adjustments, and developer needs a resolver aligned to canonical-label behavior. Preserve the 11 attributes already above 85% by not changing them.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "A realistic ceiling with current sources is about 83-84% overall, consistent with the provided ceiling estimate. releaseYear, developer, publisher, and ESRB are materially improvable through fusion changes. userScore and criticScore appear partly structurally limited because no source consistently matches validation. So substantial improvement is available, but not perfect accuracy.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "releaseYear",\n      "issue": "Current resolver/priority is wrong. Accuracy is 0% even though source-vs-validation shows metacritic exact=100%, sales exact=93%, dbpedia exact=80%, all non-null.",\n      "fix": "Change releaseYear fuser to prefer_higher_trust with trust_map={\'metacritic\':5,\'sales\':4,\'dbpedia\':1}. Do not use earliest.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Validation clearly expects a canonical source value, not the chronologically earliest one. Among all sources, metacritic matches perfectly. prefer_higher_trust is the best resolver because one source is dominant. voting could still fail when all three disagree; earliest is already catastrophic; median/maximum/minimum are inapplicable for date strings. This is the highest-confidence fusion fix.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.087\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "developer",\n      "issue": "Current voting can select alternate or expanded names, while validation often expects a canonical short form (e.g., \'Traveller\'s Tales\' over \'TT Games\', \'London Studio\' over \'SCEE London Studio\'). Missing-fused cases should also reduce after post-clustering, but resolver choice still matters.",\n      "fix": "Change developer fuser from voting to prefer_higher_trust with trust_map={\'metacritic\':4,\'sales\':4,\'dbpedia\':1}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Source comparison shows metacritic exact=80%, sales exact=80%, dbpedia exact=73%, with higher fuzzy for dbpedia due to longer/variant forms. That pattern argues against longest_string and against plain voting when alias variants split votes. prefer_higher_trust over the two best sources avoids dbpedia\'s noisier canonicalization while still allowing either strong source to win. favour_sources was considered, but there is no 